1778265446795921	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyhg0		item.create	bn-3vf5	{"description":"Problem\n-------\nAfter a successful `maw ws merge`, the epoch advances and every other workspace becomes stale. The user must run `maw ws sync --rebase <name>` per sibling before any further work. In a 5-workspace batch, that is 4 explicit syncs interleaved between merges — pure ceremony, since the existing rebase machinery already detects \"Replayed cleanly\" and produces structured conflict state when it does not.\n\nGoal\n----\nAfter a merge advances the epoch, automatically rebase every non-target workspace onto the new epoch using the existing `rebase_workspace()` machinery. Default-on, opt-out via config.\n\nDesign\n------\n- Default-on. New config key `MergeConfig.auto_rebase_siblings: bool` (default `true`) in `crates/maw-core/src/config.rs` (around line 127).\n- New CLI flag `--no-auto-rebase` on `maw ws merge` for per-invocation override.\n- Conflicts during sibling rebase are NOT treated as failure of the parent merge. The conflict-as-data model (existing) preserves conflict markers in the sibling's HEAD with sidecar metadata; merge output reports per-sibling result.\n- Skip rules per sibling (checked in this order, lock acquired before re-checking 2 and 3):\n  1. Workspace currently locked (another op in progress) → skip (\"in use\").\n  2. Workspace dirty (uncommitted changes) → skip (\"dirty\").\n  3. Workspace has merge-state.json (mid-merge from earlier in same batch) → skip (\"in progress\").\n  4. `base_epoch` already equals new epoch → skip (\"up to date\").\n  Otherwise: rebase.\n- Per-sibling result categories printed in merge output:\n  - \"rebased clean\" — replayed without conflicts\n  - \"rebased with N conflicts\" — replayed, conflict markers + sidecar present\n  - \"skipped: <reason>\"\n  - \"failed: <reason>\" — rebase machinery returned an error; log it, do not abort the merge\n\nConcurrency\n-----------\n- Acquire the existing per-workspace lock (`crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/lock.rs`) with try-lock semantics. NEVER block the merge waiting for a sibling lock.\n- Re-check dirty state and merge-state UNDER the lock, not before.\n- Per-sibling atomicity: existing `rebase_workspace` already handles ref-level atomicity for one workspace; orchestrate sequentially.\n- Do NOT modify sibling worktrees as part of auto-rebase. Advance only the refs (`refs/manifold/epoch/ws/<name>` and the workspace branch). The worktree gets updated next time the sibling agent runs a workspace command — matches existing rebase semantics, which are mostly ref-level.\n\nImplementation sketch\n---------------------\n1. After COMMIT phase succeeds (`crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/merge.rs` ~line 3286), before printing summary:\n   - Enumerate non-target workspaces.\n   - For each: try-lock → check skip rules → call `rebase_workspace(name, new_epoch)` → record result.\n2. Refactor `rebase_workspace` (`crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:137-494`) so the sibling-rebase orchestrator can call it without the print-and-return semantics. Return a result struct (`{ replayed: usize, conflicts: usize, error: Option<...> }`); existing CLI callers print from that struct.\n3. Add `auto_rebase_siblings` field to `MergeConfig` in `crates/maw-core/src/config.rs` (next to existing merge fields, ~line 127).\n4. Add `--no-auto-rebase` clap arg to `maw ws merge`.\n5. Document in CHANGELOG.md.\n\nFiles affected\n--------------\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/merge.rs` — call site after epoch advance (~3286), and CLI/options struct\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:137-494` — refactor to return structured result\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/lock.rs` — verify try-lock primitive exists; add if missing\n- `crates/maw-core/src/config.rs:127-143` — add config field with `#[serde(default)]`\n- New tests under `tests/`\n\nRisks\n-----\n- Sibling agent mid-`git diff` while we move the workspace branch ref. Refs move is atomic; the agent's git operation sees either old or new ref consistently. As long as we do not touch the worktree, there is no corruption.\n- Sibling rebase fails partway (e.g. corrupt object) — must not abort the parent merge, must surface clearly in merge output.\n- Long sibling rebase (100+ commits) blocks merge return. Acceptable for now; defer to a background-rebase job only if it becomes a problem.\n- Test combinatorics: N workspaces × {clean, conflict, dirty, locked} × {merge target, sibling}. Property tests are the right tool here.\n\nTesting\n-------\n- Unit: skip-rule matrix (one test per skip case).\n- Integration: 3-workspace batch — one sibling has clean rebase, one has conflict, one is dirty → assert correct categorization.\n- Integration: opt-out via `--no-auto-rebase` → siblings remain stale.\n- Integration: opt-out via config → same behavior.\n- Property: extend `tests/sync_proptest.rs` patterns to assert epoch monotonicity and no-work-lost across random merge sequences with auto-rebase enabled.\n- DST: failpoint between rebase orchestration steps; recovery should be a no-op (siblings remain stale, user can manually sync).\n\nSize\n----\nL — significant orchestration code, careful concurrency semantics, broad test surface.","kind":"task","labels":["ux","merge","sync","ergonomics"],"size":"l","title":"Auto-rebase sibling workspaces after maw ws merge"}	blake3:lQseQ9gTcKKOlYuU8Dm_UHX0AwjUkg8yilc9WLJaJMQ
1778265476335274	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyhw0		item.create	bn-3az5	{"description":"Problem\n-------\n`maw ws sync <name>` (no flag) currently:\n- If the workspace has no commits ahead of epoch → fast-forward checkout to new epoch (correct).\n- If the workspace HAS commits ahead → prints a warning telling the user to use `--rebase` and exits without doing anything (`crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/mod.rs:165-172`, with secondary warning at line 217).\n\nThis is failure-as-documentation. Users have to fail once to learn the right flag. `--rebase` is the correct answer >99% of the time post-merge.\n\nGoal\n----\nMake `--rebase` the default. Add `--no-rebase` for the destructive reset path. Mirror in `sync_all()`.\n\nDesign\n------\n- `maw ws sync <name>` (no flag):\n  - No commits ahead → FF checkout (unchanged).\n  - Commits ahead → rebase via existing `rebase_workspace()` (NEW: was a warning).\n  - Dirty workspace → refuse with clear error (unchanged safety guard).\n- `maw ws sync <name> --no-rebase`:\n  - No commits ahead → FF checkout.\n  - Commits ahead → REFUSE with \"would discard committed work — run `maw ws sync` (default rebases) or destroy and recreate the workspace if you really want to drop these commits.\" Do NOT do a destructive reset silently. The destructive path stays explicitly opt-in via a future `maw ws reset` or equivalent.\n- `maw ws sync --all`:\n  - Replace per-workspace `sync_worktree_to_epoch` call (line 312) with the same default-rebase logic.\n  - `--no-rebase` flag opts out, falling back to today's behavior (FF only; warn-and-skip workspaces with committed work).\n\nBackward compat\n---------------\n- `--rebase` flag becomes a no-op (since it is now the default). Accept it for one or two minor versions with a one-line deprecation hint on stderr; remove later.\n- Document in CHANGELOG.md as a behavior change. No silent destructive surprises — the only path that previously silently warned now silently does the right thing.\n\nFiles affected\n--------------\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/mod.rs:84` — `sync()` signature: change `rebase: bool` to `no_rebase: bool` (or keep `rebase` and flip default in CLI parsing — pick whichever is cleaner).\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/mod.rs:154-172` — replace warning-and-bail with rebase call.\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/mod.rs:200-217` — remove the secondary \"use --rebase\" hint.\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/mod.rs:229-357` — `sync_all()` parallel changes.\n- CLI clap definition for `maw ws sync` — flag rename / addition.\n- CHANGELOG.md — behavior change entry.\n\nTests\n-----\n- `tests/sync_rebase_semantics.rs` — add cases for default behavior == rebase.\n- New: `--no-rebase` with commits ahead refuses with clear error (no destructive reset).\n- Existing: dirty refusal preserved.\n- Existing: FF-only path on no-commits-ahead preserved.\n- Existing: `tests/sync_proptest.rs` patterns continue to pass (may need flag flips).\n\nRisks\n-----\n- Internal callers: investigation showed `sync_all()` is the main internal path; no other internal call sites of the warn-and-bail path. Verify with grep before flipping.\n- Surprise factor for users who scripted `maw ws sync` expecting a warn-and-skip on committed work. Deprecation notice + CHANGELOG should cover it; this project has one user (us).\n\nSize\n----\nS — small code surface, mostly CLI-default flip and test coverage shift.","kind":"task","labels":["ux","sync","ergonomics","breaking-change"],"size":"s","title":"Make --rebase the default for maw ws sync; add --no-rebase"}	blake3:rsExt-PS7l51LHkKDk_PsFb4KlnIR02l_0f5aCWTAk4
1778265523421684	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyiA0		item.create	bn-11ip	{"description":"Problem\n-------\nWhen the user (or a hook) commits directly to the configured target branch — including via `git commit` then `git push` from the default workspace — the next `maw ws merge` errors with:\n\n  \"Target branch 'main' has diverged from the current epoch.\n   Branch:  <oid>\n   Epoch:   <oid>\n   Direct commits were made to <ws> outside of maw.\n   To fix: run `maw epoch sync` to absorb them into the epoch, then retry.\"\n\n(`crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/merge.rs:2541-2553`)\n\nPure git would fast-forward. The maw gate exists because the epoch is the diff3 merge base for in-flight workspaces, and naïvely advancing it could change the patch interpretation for workspaces that already touched the same files. But when external commits touch ONLY files no in-flight workspace touches, advancing the epoch is provably safe.\n\nGoal\n----\nIn `maw ws merge`, when the only blocker is fast-forward divergence and a safety check passes, transparently absorb the FF range into the epoch and proceed. Default-on, opt-out via config.\n\nSafety predicate (\"FF absorb is safe\")\n--------------------------------------\n1. `epoch_oid` is a STRICT ancestor of `branch_oid` (FF, not fork).\n2. For each non-target workspace W with `base_epoch < branch_oid`:\n   - Let `ff_paths` = paths changed in `epoch_oid..branch_oid` (tree diff).\n   - Let `ws_paths` = W's touched-paths set, computed against W's actual `base_epoch` via `compute_patchset()` in `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/touched.rs:62-91`.\n   - Require `ff_paths ∩ ws_paths == ∅`.\n3. All checks performed under the same lock/transaction model as the merge precondition phase. No caching of `ws_paths` — recompute at decision time.\n\nIf any condition fails → keep the existing error message. The user can still run `maw epoch sync` manually.\n\nDesign\n------\n- Default-on. New config key `MergeConfig.auto_absorb_ff: bool` (default `true`) for parity with the auto-rebase-siblings bone.\n- The absorb itself is a single atomic ref move: `refs/manifold/epoch/current` from `epoch_oid` to `branch_oid`. Already implemented as `write_epoch_current()` in `crates/maw-core/src/refs.rs` (called from `crates/maw-cli/src/epoch.rs:55`). Reuse it.\n- Print a single stderr line on absorption: \"Absorbed N upstream commit(s) into epoch (<short_oid>..<short_oid>).\"\n- When the safety predicate fails, augment the existing error with an \"Affected workspace(s):\" line listing names that blocked, so the user knows what would have to drain before auto-absorb works.\n\nImplementation sketch\n---------------------\n1. In `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/merge.rs` precondition path (~2541-2553):\n   - Compute relationship: ancestor / descendant / fork.\n   - If strict ancestor (FF candidate):\n     - Diff `epoch_oid..branch_oid` for changed paths (use gix tree-diff helpers in `maw-git`).\n     - Enumerate non-target workspaces; collect each's touched-path set via `collect_touched_workspace()` (`crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/touched.rs:62`).\n     - Compute intersections.\n     - If all empty: call the epoch-advance primitive (extract from `crates/maw-cli/src/epoch.rs:20-65` or call `write_epoch_current` directly), print absorbed line, continue with merge precondition.\n     - If any non-empty: error with current message + \"Affected workspace(s): <names>\" line.\n   - If not strict ancestor (fork or already up-to-date with branch ahead): fall through to existing behavior.\n2. Extend post-PREPARE re-check at `merge.rs:3237-3254` for the absorbed-FF case — branch could advance again between PREPARE and COMMIT; the same safety predicate should be re-evaluated.\n3. Add `auto_absorb_ff` to `MergeConfig`.\n4. Document in CHANGELOG.md.\n\nFiles affected\n--------------\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/merge.rs:2541-2553` — precondition replacement.\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/merge.rs:3237-3254` — post-PREPARE re-check parallel update.\n- `crates/maw-core/src/config.rs:127-143` — add `auto_absorb_ff`.\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/epoch.rs:20-65` — extract a callable epoch-advance primitive (or just call `write_epoch_current` directly from merge.rs).\n- `crates/maw-git/src/...` — verify `is_ancestor` and tree-diff-by-path helpers are exposed; add if missing.\n- CHANGELOG.md.\n\nRisks\n-----\n- Race between absorb and merge COMMIT: another process advances branch again. Existing PREPARE/COMMIT model already handles reset-and-retry; the absorb fits in as one more pre-PREPARE step plus a parallel post-PREPARE check.\n- Wrong relationship classification: ensure \"ancestor\" check is STRICT (epoch is a strict ancestor of branch) — not symmetric. Use `gix-revwalk` graph queries.\n- Stale touched-set: recompute against actual `base_epoch` at decision time. No caching.\n- Workspace whose `base_epoch == old_epoch` but whose patchset is empty (e.g. workspace just created): trivially safe — empty intersection.\n- Workspace whose `base_epoch < old_epoch` (already stale before this merge attempt): include in the safety check the same way; its touched set is computed against ITS `base_epoch`, not the old global epoch.\n\nTests\n-----\n- External docs-only commit, in-flight workspace touches code only → absorbed silently, merge proceeds.\n- External commit touches file workspace also touches → blocked with augmented error listing the workspace.\n- Fork divergence (epoch and branch both have unique commits) → blocked with current error, NOT absorbed.\n- No in-flight workspaces other than target → trivially safe, absorbed.\n- Multiple FF commits in range → all absorbed at once.\n- Workspace with empty patchset → trivially safe.\n- Concurrency: two merges race during absorb; one wins, other re-evaluates cleanly.\n- DST: failpoint between absorb and PREPARE → re-run sees absorbed epoch and proceeds.\n\nOpen question (track separately)\n--------------------------------\nShould `maw epoch sync` (the manual command at `crates/maw-cli/src/epoch.rs:20`) pick up the same safety check, refusing to advance if it would invalidate an in-flight workspace? Current behavior is unconditional advance. Recommendation: yes, with `--force` to override — but file as a follow-up bone to keep this one scoped.\n\nSize\n----\nM — focused change, but the safety predicate deserves unit tests at the predicate level (not just integration). Allocate time for the gix-side helpers if missing.","kind":"task","labels":["ux","merge","epoch","ergonomics"],"size":"m","title":"Auto-absorb fast-forward divergence in maw ws merge"}	blake3:eq1CX5WwkejXpX-zC7C018EQhgP9hNInFBduVdp82sw
1778266961954505	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyiQ0		item.move	bn-3az5	{"state":"doing"}	blake3:t3FwR1mX4dNhSZQcB2aDtOtGuGNieiVB9IxBFCVZFc8
