1778284711392815	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyng0		item.create	bn-28q2	{"description":"Problem\n-------\nDuring the bn-3mbj merge today, after committing two small fixes directly to default (`b193dba` test fix and `06dcecd` proptest seeds), `maw ws merge bn-3mbj --into default` errored:\n\n```\nTarget branch 'main' has diverged from the current epoch.\n  Branch:  06dcecdb1c43\n  Epoch:   3c9741136e03\n  Direct commits were made to default outside of maw.\nTo fix: run `maw epoch sync` to absorb them into the epoch, then retry.\n  Affected workspace(s): default\n```\n\nThe new \"Affected workspace(s)\" line (added by bn-11ip) names `default` as the blocker. But `default` is also the merge TARGET. The FF range is exactly the diff between the old epoch and what's currently in default. Of course default's touched-set intersects the FF range — those commits ARE the FF range.\n\nThis makes the FF-absorb feature useless in the most common case: the user makes a small commit directly on default and then tries to merge another workspace.\n\nGoal\n----\nExclude the merge target itself from the touched-set safety check. The FF-absorb is being asked: \"is it safe to advance the epoch to include these new commits in default, before merging in the named workspace?\" The new workspace's diff is computed against the post-FF epoch anyway, and default's \"touched paths\" being the FF range itself is tautological.\n\nDesign\n------\nIn the safety predicate (`crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/ff_absorb.rs` or wherever the workspace iteration lives, plus the call site at `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/merge.rs:2541-2553`):\n\n- Take a `target_workspace: &str` parameter (the `--into` target).\n- When iterating non-target workspaces for the safety check, ALSO skip the target.\n- The current code likely says \"for each non-target workspace W…\" but is using a too-narrow definition of \"non-target\" (probably \"not the source workspace being merged\"). Widen it to include the target.\n\nFiles affected\n--------------\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/ff_absorb.rs` — the safety predicate.\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/merge.rs` — pass the merge target into the predicate.\n\nTests\n-----\n- Direct commit on default → `maw ws merge <other> --into default` absorbs FF and proceeds, no manual `maw epoch sync` required.\n- Direct commit on a branch-attached workspace → `maw ws merge <src> --into ws:<bound>` similarly absorbs.\n- The existing block-when-non-target-workspace-is-affected case still works: another in-flight workspace touches a file in the FF range → blocked with the workspace name listed.\n- Multiple in-flight workspaces, only target affected → absorbed (this is the regression case).\n- Multiple in-flight workspaces, target affected AND another is too → blocked, listing only the non-target as affected.\n\nRisks\n-----\nNone significant — the bn-11ip safety check was already excluding the merge SOURCE; this just widens \"non-target\" to include the merge TARGET as well.\n\nSize\n----\nS — one-line change, primarily test coverage.","kind":"bug","labels":["correctness","merge","followup-bn-11ip"],"size":"s","title":"FF-absorb predicate must exclude the merge target from the touched-set check"}	blake3:slZqI_7ywFJHrNmff2pcp-frLKTPh2dknif4lrntZlU
1778284756944599	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEynw0		item.move	bn-28q2	{"state":"doing"}	blake3:lgtGGHcgLM2dMxyaPNfAMlzosFeEi2t8PiS18dBoIFA
