1777914233947947	codex	itc:v3:AWKcyTkmSTnJOZEAAAAAQbtXVqu6u0AAAAEzAQ		item.create	bn-m7as	{"description":"# Context\nWhile using MAW in `/home/bob/src/liveramp/crib`, we created two ephemeral workspaces from branch `crib-graph`:\n\n- `crib2-command-map`\n- `crib2-segment-inventory`\n\nThe intended integration target was an existing workspace named `crib2`, located at `ws/crib2`, on branch `crib-graph`.\n\nUser-level desired workflow:\n\n```bash\nmaw ws create <work-name> --from crib-graph\nmaw exec <work-name> -- <command>\nmaw ws merge <work-name> --into crib2 --destroy\n```\n\n# Failure\nRunning the intended merge command failed:\n\n```bash\nmaw ws merge crib2-command-map --into crib2 --destroy\n```\n\nObserved error:\n\n```text\nError: Workspace 'crib2' is not bound to a change and cannot be used as --into target.\n  Use one of:\n    --into default\n    --into <change-id>\n```\n\nThis was surprising because `maw ws merge --help` says `--into` is an explicit merge target described as \"workspace name or change id\", and `maw ws list` showed `crib2` as a workspace:\n\n```text\ndefault                 /home/bob/src/liveramp/crib/ws/default\ncrib2                   /home/bob/src/liveramp/crib/ws/crib2        # crib graph\ncrib2-command-map       /home/bob/src/liveramp/crib/ws/crib2-command-map\ncrib2-segment-inventory /home/bob/src/liveramp/crib/ws/crib2-segment-inventory\n```\n\n# Attempted Workaround\nI then tried to create a tracked change from `crib-graph`, expecting to get a change id that MAW would allow as a merge target:\n\n```bash\nmaw changes create \"Crib 2\" --from crib-graph --workspace crib2 --format json\n```\n\nThat failed while creating the generated feature branch:\n\n```text\nError: Failed to create branch 'feat/ch-34x-crib-2': fatal: cannot lock ref 'refs/heads/feat/ch-34x-crib-2': unable to create directory for /home/bob/src/liveramp/crib/repo.git/refs/heads/feat/ch-34x-crib-2\n```\n\nI checked for an existing flat `feat` ref that might block nested refs and did not find one:\n\n```bash\ngit --git-dir=repo.git show-ref --heads\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```text\ncf804f60c0141bcf2381c4b713591fcdd5b8fc90 refs/heads/DV-13800\ncf804f60c0141bcf2381c4b713591fcdd5b8fc90 refs/heads/crib-graph\nd462bdf5509aa589c9ba37b893798bc5e5506dbd refs/heads/main\n```\n\nI also tried a direct branch creation to confirm the underlying Git failure:\n\n```bash\ngit --git-dir=repo.git branch feat/test-branch crib-graph\n```\n\nObserved:\n\n```text\nfatal: cannot lock ref 'refs/heads/feat/test-branch': unable to create directory for repo.git/refs/heads/feat/test-branch\n```\n\n# Bad Next Step / UX Trap\nI attempted to manually create `repo.git/refs/heads/feat` as a diagnostic/repair step. In the Codex sandbox this hit a read-only-filesystem boundary and asked for escalation. The user interrupted and correctly questioned why we were manually touching Git internals.\n\nThis seems like a MAW UX issue even if the underlying Git ref-directory issue is environmental: the user wanted to merge into an existing workspace, MAW rejected the workspace target, the documented help text says workspace targets are valid, and the fallback path led toward low-level Git metadata repair.\n\n# Expected Behavior\nOne of these should be true:\n\n1. `maw ws merge <worker> --into crib2 --destroy` should work when `crib2` is an existing workspace, or\n2. The error/help text should clearly state that only `default` and active change ids are supported targets, not arbitrary workspace names, or\n3. MAW should offer a first-class command to bind an existing workspace/branch as a change target, without requiring manual branch/ref manipulation.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Clarify whether `maw ws merge --into <workspace>` is intended to support non-default workspaces.\n- [ ] If yes, fix merge target resolution so existing workspace `crib2` works.\n- [ ] If no, update `maw ws merge --help` and the error message to remove or qualify \"workspace name\".\n- [ ] Provide a documented safe path for turning an existing workspace/branch such as `crib2` / `crib-graph` into an active change target.\n- [ ] Investigate why `maw changes create` could not create `refs/heads/feat/...` in this repo, or surface a clearer actionable diagnostic.","kind":"bug","title":"MAW cannot merge into existing crib2 workspace because it is not bound to a change"}	blake3:02bk08rvysztWHMzIHvvc26OmtvweE0jzMnSo-X41bU
1777914997315722	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy3gw		item.update	bn-m7as	{"field":"title","value":"Clarify or support non-default workspace merge targets"}	blake3:MYsdbXdhGbXct5S8MOu5H4fuY9WQ9WHrzsJjkt2R9IM
1777914997333673	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy3ww		item.update	bn-m7as	{"field":"description","value":"# Context\nIn `/home/bob/src/liveramp/crib`, work was split across ephemeral workspaces created from branch `crib-graph`:\n\n- `crib2-command-map`\n- `crib2-segment-inventory`\n\nThe intended integration target was an existing persistent workspace named `crib2`, located at `ws/crib2`, also on the `crib-graph` line of work.\n\nDesired workflow:\n\n```bash\nmaw ws create <work-name> --from crib-graph\nmaw exec <work-name> -- <command>\nmaw ws merge <work-name> --into crib2 --destroy\n```\n\n# Failure\nRunning this failed:\n\n```bash\nmaw ws merge crib2-command-map --into crib2 --destroy\n```\n\nObserved error:\n\n```text\nError: Workspace 'crib2' is not bound to a change and cannot be used as --into target.\n  Use one of:\n    --into default\n    --into <change-id>\n```\n\nThis is surprising because `maw ws merge --help` describes `--into` as an explicit merge target with \"workspace name or change id\", and `maw ws list` showed `crib2` as a workspace:\n\n```text\ndefault                 /home/bob/src/liveramp/crib/ws/default\ncrib2                   /home/bob/src/liveramp/crib/ws/crib2        # crib graph\ncrib2-command-map       /home/bob/src/liveramp/crib/ws/crib2-command-map\ncrib2-segment-inventory /home/bob/src/liveramp/crib/ws/crib2-segment-inventory\n```\n\n# Current Code Behavior\n`resolve_merge_target` currently accepts:\n\n1. the configured default workspace,\n2. an active change id, or\n3. a workspace name only when that workspace metadata is already bound to an active change.\n\nSo an unbound persistent workspace like `crib2` is rejected by design, but the CLI help implies it should be accepted.\n\n# Non-Issue From Original Report\nThe earlier `maw changes create` branch creation failure appears to have been caused by Codex sandboxing or a transient environment issue, not by MAW. The crib repo now has `refs/heads/feat/ch-34x-crib-2`, and `maw changes list` shows active change `ch-34x`.\n\nDo not spend this bone manually repairing Git ref directories. The current safe workaround for the crib case is to merge into the active change target:\n\n```bash\nmaw ws merge crib2-command-map --into ch-34x --destroy --message \"...\"\n```\n\n# Expected Behavior\nPick and implement one clear product contract:\n\n1. Support `maw ws merge <worker> --into <existing-non-default-workspace>` for persistent workspaces like `crib2`, or\n2. Keep the current restriction and update help/error text so users are told that `--into` supports only the default workspace, active change ids, or change-bound workspaces.\n\nIf option 1 is too large or unsafe, option 2 is acceptable as the minimal bug fix.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Decide whether arbitrary non-default workspace targets are supported.\n- [ ] If supported, fix merge target resolution so existing persistent workspace targets like `crib2` work safely.\n- [ ] If not supported, update `maw ws merge --help` to remove or qualify \"workspace name\".\n- [ ] If not supported, update the rejection message to explain that unbound persistent workspaces cannot be merge targets and point users to `--into default` or `--into <active-change-id>`.\n- [ ] Document or surface the safe path for turning existing workspace/branch work into an active change target without manual Git ref manipulation.\n- [ ] Add or update tests for the chosen behavior."}	blake3:7vtT85VD7acP7WueKtlgpDQ2johMmayLtwhfuKWSf_k
