1778285252862801	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyoQ0		item.move	bn-28q2	{"state":"done"}	blake3:yyqFlkGNTU9ooWDuiDuEkCYfs5l07SjMMiGsGP_GckI
1778368422393213	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyog0		item.create	bn-3r8s	{"description":"Problem (severe — silent code corruption, third occurrence of structured-conflict-layer producing wrong output)\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nReported by external agent on 2026-05-09 (still on old binary). During rebase of bn-4c6g, a Rust source file went from 12,402 lines to 35,089 lines (~2.83×) with 6 duplicate `impl SynthHandler` blocks. The output failed to compile with 22 errors (all \"type str cannot be known at compilation time\") because duplicate function definitions caused wrong overload selection.\n\nThe rebase reported `Rebase complete: 1 commit(s) replayed cleanly.` — no conflicts surfaced, no warning. The agent's workaround: destroy the workspace, recreate from main, manually re-apply the 5-line `synth_handler` change via Edit tool, force-merge.\n\nPattern with prior reports:\n- 2026-05-08 bn-2ghz → `--keep <ws>` clobbered 377 lines of merged-in sibling content. Fixed in bn-3mbj.\n- 2026-05-09 bn-4c6g → silent triplication of file content during rebase replay.\n\nHypothesized causes (need verification)\n---------------------------------------\nThe 2.83× ratio with 6 duplicate impl blocks (likely 2 → 6, i.e. 3× the impl count) strongly suggests one of:\n\n1. **Hunk misalignment on structurally similar regions.** A file with many sibling `impl Trait for X { fn handle(...) {...} }` blocks looks repetitive to a line-based diff3. If the workspace's hunk anchored on one impl block, the merge engine could splice it after multiple matching blocks. `try_clean_three_way_overlap` (`crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:1003-1045`) calls `merge_text` (gix's `builtin_driver::text`); the bug would be upstream of maw OR in our hunk-window tuning if any.\n\n2. **PatchSet over-application across multiple commits.** The rebase loop at `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:455-` calls `apply_unilateral_patchset` per commit. If a commit's patchset contains an Added entry that should be Modified (or vice-versa), the unilateral apply could append content instead of merging it. With 1 workspace commit replayed and 3 occurrences, this hypothesis would mean the engine accidentally applied the same patch 3 times across the parent chain.\n\n3. **Rename + modify confusion.** If the file was renamed and modified, a buggy rename detection could insert the new content twice (once at the old path that gets resolved-as-add and once at the new path).\n\n4. **`promote_overlaps_to_conflicts` misclassification.** The pre-pass at `rebase.rs:500-508` may install a synthetic conflict that then gets \"resolved\" by the V1 collapse (line 510-519) in a way that duplicates content.\n\nGoal\n----\n1. Reproduce. The agent reported they're on the OLD binary (pre-bn-3mbj merges); first thing is to test if the bug still reproduces on current main. If yes, file size / hunk-alignment investigation. If no, identify which fix resolved it and add a regression test anyway.\n2. Fix the root cause.\n3. Add a regression test built from a repetitive-impl Rust file pattern.\n\nReproduction recipe (to attempt)\n--------------------------------\n1. Create a Rust file with ~10 `impl Trait for Type { fn method() {...} }` blocks where each block is structurally identical except for the type name.\n2. Make it ~12k lines (pad with realistic-looking code in each block — generated test fixtures are fine).\n3. Create a workspace, modify ONE block (add a 5-line method), commit.\n4. On default, push a sibling commit that touches a DIFFERENT block in the same file.\n5. Rebase the workspace onto the new epoch.\n6. Inspect the resulting file. Does it have duplicated content?\n\nIf the simple recipe doesn't reproduce, try variants: rename the file in the workspace; add a chmod (mode change); have the workspace's commit touch multiple impl blocks; have the epoch's commit touch the SAME blocks the workspace touches (force structured conflict).\n\nFiles to investigate first\n--------------------------\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:455-650` — main rebase loop.\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:1003-1045` — `try_clean_three_way_overlap` (the 3-way merge call site).\n- `crates/maw-core/src/merge/build.rs` (or wherever `apply_unilateral_patchset` lives) — patchset application.\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:promote_overlaps_to_conflicts` — pre-pass overlap classification.\n- `crates/maw-git/src/merge.rs:112` — `merge_text_with_style` (the gix wrapper).\n\nPriority\n--------\nURGENT. Third silent-corruption issue from this layer. Each one risks shipping broken code if the user doesn't manually inspect. Even with bn-3mbj's fix landed, the underlying merge layer can still produce wrong output without raising any signal.\n\nSize\n----\nL — investigation-heavy; root cause may be in maw-core's patchset semantics or in gix's diff3 (less likely but possible).\n\nTest plan\n---------\n- Unit (maw-git): file with ~50 nearly-identical impl blocks, modify one block in \"ours\", different block in \"theirs\", merge. Assert (a) file size doesn't blow up, (b) every block appears exactly once, (c) workspace's edit is present.\n- Property: random files with N copies of a small impl-block pattern; random edits to one or two blocks; assert post-merge file has exactly N + (edits-that-add-content) lines, no duplication.\n- Integration (rebase): the full reproduction recipe above. Failure mode that should fail-loud: file size > 1.5× max(base, epoch, ws) without a corresponding number of conflict markers.\n\nOpen questions\n--------------\n- Did this happen on the OLD binary only? Test current main first. If reproduced on main, it survived through bn-3vf5/bn-103k/bn-3mbj — so it's NOT the same bug as bn-3mbj. Different code path.\n- Does the agent's bn-4c6g workspace's commit history suggest multiple commits or just one? \"1 commit(s) replayed\" says one, but the patchset machinery might be doing more under the hood.\n- Is this an interaction with bn-3vf5's auto-rebase-siblings? If the workspace was rebased twice (e.g. once during a prior auto-rebase, once during manual sync), could state accumulate?","kind":"bug","labels":["correctness","data-loss","rebase","merge"],"size":"l","title":"Rebase silently triplicated file content while reporting clean replay","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:5AOpRfB7W8ha0MRCWFcKLmsLZ84i2ctH4Z96wRlDj6o
1778368455703016	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyow0		item.create	bn-2upt	{"description":"Problem\n-------\nThe structured-conflict layer has now produced wrong output silently in three batches:\n- bn-2ghz `--keep <ws>` clobber (root cause fixed in bn-3mbj).\n- bn-4c6g rebase triplication (under investigation in bn-3r8s).\n- (Earlier reports of similar shape.)\n\nEach time the rebase reported `replayed cleanly` and only the user's manual inspection caught the corruption. Even with the underlying root causes fixed, defense in depth would catch future regressions before they ship. This bone adds a minimal sanity check that runs at the END of `rebase_workspace_run` and before the rebased commit is finalized.\n\nGoal\n----\nAdd a content-sanity check. If a rebased file's output is structurally implausible compared to its inputs, refuse to mark the rebase as \"clean\" and surface a warning (or block the rebase, behind a config opt-out).\n\nDesign\n------\nTwo checks, ordered cheapest first:\n\n1. **Size-delta sanity.** For each modified file F with a \"clean\" merge result:\n   - Let `ours_size`, `theirs_size`, `base_size` = byte sizes of ours/theirs/base blobs.\n   - Compute `expected_max = max(ours_size, theirs_size) + max(0, theirs_size - base_size + ours_size - base_size)` — i.e. base + each side's added-bytes delta.\n   - If `merged_size > 1.5 * expected_max`, flag as suspicious. Threshold tunable.\n   - This catches the bn-4c6g pattern (output 2.83× max input).\n\n2. **AST parse sanity (where applicable).** If the file path matches an AST language pack already configured for AST merge (`crates/maw-core/src/config.rs:AstConfig`), attempt to tree-sitter-parse the output. If it parses with errors when both inputs parsed cleanly, flag as suspicious. Reuses existing tree-sitter integration; no new deps.\n\nBoth checks produce a `Suspicious { reason }` outcome. The rebase machinery's response:\n- If running under `merge ws-merge` and `merge.strict_post_rebase_check = true` (default `true`): treat as a textual conflict, preserve marker tree (best effort), mark workspace as conflicted-but-rebased. User runs `maw ws resolve`.\n- If `false`: emit a stderr WARNING line with the path and reason, but accept the merge.\n\nThe strict-by-default opt-out is the right call after three reports — silent corruption is worse than false positives.\n\nFiles affected\n--------------\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs` — add post-merge sanity check after each `try_clean_three_way_overlap` success.\n- `crates/maw-core/src/config.rs:MergeConfig` — add `strict_post_rebase_check: bool` (default `true`) and optional `post_rebase_size_ratio_max: f64` (default `1.5`).\n- `crates/maw-core/src/merge/...` — verify the AST machinery exposes a \"just parse, don't merge\" entry point.\n\nTests\n-----\n- File where merged output is exactly 3× max input → flagged.\n- File where merged output is reasonably-sized cumulative additions → NOT flagged.\n- Rust file where output fails to parse but inputs parse cleanly → flagged via AST check.\n- Suspicious flag converts to conflict-tree state when `strict_post_rebase_check = true`.\n- Opt-out with `strict_post_rebase_check = false` → warning printed, merge accepted.\n\nBackward compat\n---------------\n- New config field, default `true`. Some existing workspaces with weird-but-correct merges (e.g. legitimately added 2× content via accumulated commits) might trip the size check. Tune threshold if needed; the AST check is more precise but only covers some languages.\n\nRisks\n-----\n- False positives could block legitimate large-add merges. The 1.5× threshold gives lots of headroom; legitimate doublings are rare and the user can pass `--no-strict-post-rebase` if blocked. Default-on is the right call given the corruption reports.\n- AST parse cost on large files. Bound by the existing AST pack opt-in; non-AST paths skip parsing.\n\nSize\n----\nM — cleanly scoped, but the integration with the conflict-tree state needs care (writing a Suspicious result through the same channels as a textual conflict).\n\nOpen questions\n--------------\n- Should this run during `maw ws merge` BUILD too? Probably yes — same machinery, same risk. Scope to follow-up if too much for one bone.\n- Should the size-ratio threshold be per-file-extension (looser for generated files like Cargo.lock)? Likely yes; track separately.","kind":"task","labels":["correctness","rebase","defense-in-depth"],"size":"m","title":"Post-rebase output sanity check (size delta + AST parse where available)"}	blake3:sy6w2co8AsIc5NWNAKs1LbKCpkasZZSUcCb82xFkkyE
