1778965653270144	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEykw8		item.create	bn-imw8	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nDecide HOW the DST drives maw and injects faults, because that single\ndecision shapes every other SG1 task. Output is an ADR, not code.\n\nWHY THIS IS A SPIKE / WHAT WE DON'T KNOW\nThe FP_* failpoints (crates/maw-core/src/failpoints.rs) can ONLY be set\nprogrammatically via failpoints::set(), are compiled out unless built with\n--features failpoints, and have NO env/IPC bridge. The chaos session that\nfound bn-cm63 had to widen merge windows with a \"sleep 5\" validation\ncommand and external SIGKILL because there is no deterministic in-process\nfault control today. We do not yet know whether the DST should link\nmaw-core as a library (fast, deterministic, but cannot faithfully test\nreal process-kill crash recovery) or spawn real `maw` subprocesses\n(faithful to crash/concurrency reality, slower, harder to make\ndeterministic), nor how much of crates/maw-assurance (oracle/model/trace,\n--features assurance) is reusable.\n\nAPPROACH\n1. Read crates/maw-core/src/failpoints.rs, crates/maw-core/src/merge_state.rs\n   (the Prepare->Build->Validate->Commit->Cleanup FSM), and skim\n   crates/maw-assurance.\n2. Prototype BOTH: (a) in-process: link maw-core, run an op sequence, set\n   failpoints via failpoints::set(); (b) subprocess: spawn `maw`, inject\n   faults via a NEW env bridge (e.g. MAW_FP=\"FP_NAME=panic|abort\") added to\n   failpoints::check(), plus real SIGKILL at FP_COMMIT_BETWEEN_CAS_OPS /\n   FP_CLEANUP_*.\n3. Measure determinism (seed replay bit-exact?), throughput, and crash\n   fidelity for each.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- ADR committed under notes/ recommending: in-proc vs subprocess vs hybrid;\n  the failpoint external-control mechanism (and whether to add the env\n  bridge to failpoints.rs); a maw-assurance reuse map (% reusable, gaps).\n- A minimal working prototype runs >=1 fault-injected op-sequence\n  end-to-end, reproducible from a seed.\n\nCONTEXT POINTERS\ncrates/maw-core/src/failpoints.rs ; crates/maw-core/src/merge_state.rs ;\ncrates/maw-assurance/ ; bn-cm63 (chaos repro pattern: sleep-validation +\nsetsid + poll .manifold/merge-state.json + SIGKILL) ; goal bn-142y.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","dst","spike"],"parent":"bn-3nw1","size":"m","title":"SP1 (spike) DST execution model + failpoint control mechanism"}	blake3:QkjSR2fekp7Nncg_nKo8ksCl4QOp_TbbOHeE6XWOyJ8
1778965653507775	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEylA8		item.create	bn-3qxi	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nProve the two oracles are correctly DEFINABLE and cheaply COMPUTABLE after\nevery op-step, before T1.3/T1.4 build them.\n\nWHAT WE DON'T KNOW\nWhether \"every commit ever reachable from any workspace ref is still\nreachable from {default history} U {recovery refs} U {extant workspaces}\"\ncan be tracked incrementally without prohibitive cost, and the exact\ncoherence predicate that would have caught bn-cm63 (a dangling\nrefs/manifold/head/<ws> blob with no workspace — NOT a work-loss bug).\n\nAPPROACH\nOn a throwaway repo, drive create/commit/merge/destroy/recover, maintain\nthe historical set of all workspace ref tips ever observed, and after each\nstep compute: Oracle A = reachability closure check; Oracle B = (no\ndangling refs/manifold/head/*, merge-state.json consistent with refs, no\norphaned recovery). Plant a synthetic work-loss and a synthetic bn-cm63;\nconfirm each oracle flags its violation. Measure per-step cost; extrapolate\nto >=1e6 steps.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Written, precise predicates for Oracle A and Oracle B handed to T1.3/T1.4.\n- Prototype detects BOTH planted violations; measured per-step cost\n  documented as acceptable (or a mitigation proposed) for 1e6+ steps.\n\nCONTEXT POINTERS\nrefs/manifold/head/<ws> (oplog head blob), refs/manifold/epoch/current,\nrefs/manifold/epoch/ws/<ws>, refs/manifold/recovery/<ws>/<ts> ;\nws/default/AGENTS.md (Prime Invariant definition) ; bn-cm63 ;\nnotes/incident-lost-commits-2026-02-05.md (what real work-loss looked like).\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","dst","spike"],"parent":"bn-3nw1","size":"s","title":"SP2 (spike) Oracle A/B definition + computability validation"}	blake3:KPRyTFKT0FZi14J2XWH-Xo4jyWFYTMll3fYO95cE7FQ
1778965653761374	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEylQ8		item.create	bn-kwm7	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nProduce the SG1 architecture doc that every other T1.x task implements\nagainst, consuming SP1's execution-model ADR and SP2's oracle predicates.\n\nSCOPE\nDefine: the scenario+condition generator interface (shared with SG2 — see\nT2.1), the fault-injection layer, Oracle A and Oracle B integration points,\nthe seed/determinism contract, the shrinker, and CI wiring. Enumerate the\nconcrete remaining SG1 tasks and their order.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Doc reviewed and committed under notes/.\n- It references SP1's chosen execution model and SP2's oracle predicates.\n- The generator interface section is explicitly designed to be consumed by\n  both the cheap model driver (this sub-goal) and the real-agent driver\n  (SG2/T2.1) — \"build once, drive two ways\".\n\nDEPENDS ON: SP1, SP2.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: SP1 ADR + SP2 predicates (notes/) ; crates/maw-assurance ;\ncrates/maw-core/src/merge_state.rs.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","dst"],"parent":"bn-3nw1","size":"m","title":"T1.1 Design the DST architecture document"}	blake3:ugG3F2_j5TZkU1dUPFmmO0QwgJH0BM7IY1FbV2VZbd8
1778965653999955	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEylg8		item.create	bn-1f53	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nImplement the deterministic generator producing random VALID op-sequences\nover N workspaces, plus a parameterized condition profile. This is the\nsingle highest-leverage task: it is also the substrate SG2's agent\nbenchmark consumes (T2.1).\n\nDETAIL\nOperations: ws create / edit files / commit / merge (--into, --destroy) /\nsync / destroy / recover. Conditions (all seed-driven): concurrency degree,\nmid-op kill probability, overlapping-edit rate, stale-workspace rate.\nOutput must be a replayable trace: same seed => identical op-sequence AND\ncondition profile.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Given a seed, two runs emit byte-identical op+condition traces.\n- Generator only emits ops valid in the current model state (no nonsense\n  sequences) yet can reach hostile interleavings (concurrent merge+destroy\n  of same ws, like the bn-cm63 repro).\n- Interface matches the T1.1 design and is consumable by T2.1.\n\nDEPENDS ON: T1.1 (design), SP1 (execution model).\nCONTEXT POINTERS: T1.1 doc ; the bn-cm63 chaos repro is the canonical\nhostile interleaving to ensure is reachable.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","dst"],"parent":"bn-3nw1","size":"l","title":"T1.2 Build the scenario + condition generator (shared substrate)"}	blake3:V9SF5LIhjJCDNunAPZeMXbG9oCEOA3rm-qgP_-EqmbE
1778965654240741	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEylw8		item.create	bn-1z8q	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nImplement the reachability oracle from SP2's predicate: after EVERY step,\nevery commit ever reachable from any workspace ref must still be reachable\nfrom {default branch history} U {refs/manifold/recovery/*} U {extant\nworkspace refs}. Maintain the historical tip set across the run.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Removing the bn-cm63 fix OR planting a deliberate work-loss makes Oracle\n  A fail with a minimal seed.\n- Zero false positives across a clean 1e5-step smoke run.\n- Per-step cost within the SP2 budget.\n\nDEPENDS ON: SP2 (predicate), T1.2 (generator).\nCONTEXT POINTERS: SP2 predicate ; refs/manifold/recovery/<ws>/<ts> ;\nnotes/incident-lost-commits-2026-02-05.md.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","dst"],"parent":"bn-3nw1","size":"l","title":"T1.3 Implement Oracle A — no committed work lost"}	blake3:TcJ1mqTc7znNMmH0SuPKdZuxm9QA-TWTFX4d7UuLZpw
1778965654482368	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEymA8		item.create	bn-3ji6	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nImplement the coherence oracle from SP2: no dangling refs/manifold/head/*\nfor non-existent workspaces; .manifold/merge-state.json consistent with\nrefs; no orphaned recovery. bn-cm63 was exactly this class (no work lost,\nbut a real defect doctor caught) — Oracle A alone would have missed it.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- A synthetic bn-cm63 (destroy racing in-flight merge of same ws) is\n  flagged by Oracle B.\n- Agrees with `maw doctor`'s stale-head-ref / merge-state checks on a\n  battery of hand-built incoherent states.\n\nDEPENDS ON: SP2, T1.2.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: bn-cm63 (root cause: record_merge_operations ->\nensure_workspace_oplog_head re-bootstraps a deleted head ref) ;\ncrates/maw-cli/src/ref_gc.rs (prune_dangling_head_refs) ;\ncrates/maw-cli/src/doctor.rs.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","dst"],"parent":"bn-3nw1","size":"m","title":"T1.4 Implement Oracle B — state coherence"}	blake3:xwwntI1R7wfn2ZizRDZtowDZP29NR0DA-aooIdNrU2M
1778965654728602	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEymQ8		item.create	bn-263u	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nImplement the fault layer per SP1's chosen mechanism: drive faults at named\nFP_* points AND real SIGKILL at the dangerous boundaries\n(FP_COMMIT_BETWEEN_CAS_OPS, FP_COMMIT_AFTER_EPOCH_CAS,\nFP_COMMIT_BEFORE_BRANCH_CAS, FP_CLEANUP_*, FP_PREPARE_*).\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- The harness can deterministically crash a merge at any named phase from\n  a seed.\n- If SP1 chose the env-bridge: failpoints.rs has a tested\n  env->FailpointAction parser gated behind --features failpoints.\n- Post-crash, recovery (maw ws merge --abort / retry) is exercisable by the\n  harness so Oracles A/B run on the recovered state.\n\nDEPENDS ON: SP1.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: crates/maw-core/src/failpoints.rs (full FP_* list) ;\ncrates/maw-core/src/merge_state.rs (recovery_outcome_for_phase, staleness) ;\nbn-2wyh (crash recovery semantics).\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","dst"],"parent":"bn-3nw1","size":"m","title":"T1.5 Fault injection: FP_* failpoints + real process kills"}	blake3:Ra2HtdiFv9axVjH0kKUWkMvBF3xLJskd4ux7Lo11rOI
1778965654964028	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEymg8		item.create	bn-32k3	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nGuarantee bit-exact seed replay and, on any oracle violation, automatically\nshrink the op-sequence to a minimal reproducing case.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- A planted bug reduces to a <10-step minimal seed automatically.\n- Re-running a failing seed reproduces the identical violation 10/10 times.\n\nDEPENDS ON: T1.2, T1.3, T1.4, T1.5.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: T1.1 determinism contract.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","dst"],"parent":"bn-3nw1","size":"m","title":"T1.6 Determinism guarantee + failing-seed shrinker"}	blake3:hJ9-82-hEt4p1GY0_ylWyP73OUfU6nxr3TutRT24Mwg
1778965655212291	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEymw8		item.create	bn-1gp4	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nRun a bounded DST budget on every commit and a long soak nightly; on\nfailure emit the seed + minimized trace as a CI artifact.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- A deliberately re-introduced regression fails CI with an actionable seed\n  in the artifact.\n- Per-commit budget keeps CI under an agreed wall-clock cap (state it).\n\nDEPENDS ON: T1.6.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: existing CI config ; just check gates.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","dst"],"parent":"bn-3nw1","size":"m","title":"T1.7 CI integration: bounded per-commit + nightly soak"}	blake3:i5j6mquyAqBUqnvzMcwkpt3JMgbYWPngfOEb0GEpXLU
1778965655440890	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEynA8		item.create	bn-3ryq	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nEncode known historical failures as permanent must-catch seeds: bn-cm63\n(destroy vs in-flight merge head-ref leak) and the\nnotes/incident-lost-commits-2026-02-05.md scenario.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Reverting the bn-cm63 fix turns the corpus run RED via Oracle B.\n- Simulating the documented lost-commits incident turns it RED via Oracle A.\n- Corpus runs in CI (part of T1.7).\n\nDEPENDS ON: T1.3, T1.4.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: bn-cm63 ; notes/incident-lost-commits-2026-02-05.md.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","dst"],"parent":"bn-3nw1","size":"s","title":"T1.8 Permanent regression-seed corpus"}	blake3:T-3dHa-UzWj7rdn-mS88tuv8QOjz6UUAuCDGD-yJd6A
1778965655723584	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEynQ8		item.create	bn-6308	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nRun the harness to the target volume and record machine-checked evidence\nthat Oracle A and Oracle B never fired — the centerpiece of the v1.0\nsafety claim.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Define and justify the target (proposal: >=1e9 fault-injected op-steps\n  across the full condition spectrum).\n- Recorded result: zero Oracle A/B violations at that volume, reproducible\n  from the published seed range.\n- Output is consumable by SG5/T5.2 (publication). GATES the release.\n\nDEPENDS ON: T1.7, T1.8.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: goal bn-142y hard gates ; SG5/T5.2.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","dst"],"parent":"bn-3nw1","size":"m","title":"T1.9 Soak campaign + published zero-violation evidence"}	blake3:qKXKNmYk08kRHwyO2HBk5ysZBUFKIwS-qrKi2KHIDfM
1778965655723803	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyng8		item.link	bn-3ctu	{"link_type":"blocks","target":"bn-6308"}	blake3:EGZYebcXnqoLSVyeQA3A7mjpsAbw_aGxXfMseY-fG9s
1778965655960948	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEynw8		item.create	bn-2ixm	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nProve the agent benchmark is feasible AND fair before building it: pick a\nreproducible agent-driver harness, size cost/variance, and confirm the\njj-workspaces arm can actually reproduce jj's opfork-wedge failure (else\nthe comparison is a strawman and non-credible).\n\nWHAT WE DON'T KNOW\nHow to run fresh-context agents reproducibly at sufficient N within cost;\nhow much run-to-run variance the metrics have; whether current jj still\nexhibits the shared-oplog opfork cascade described in notes/manifold-v2.md\nsection 2.2 under concurrent workspace use (if it no longer does, that\nmaterially changes the v1.0 comparison story and must be surfaced).\n\nAPPROACH\nStand up a minimal 2-task / 3-agent harness. Run it once each on: maw,\ngit-worktrees + a thin coordination convention, and jj-workspaces. For jj,\ndeliberately drive concurrent workspace ops and confirm opfork / stale /\ndivergent-op symptoms reproduce. Record per-run cost and metric variance.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Feasibility memo (notes/) with: chosen agent-driver harness; measured\n  per-run cost + metric variance; required N for signal; a DEMONSTRATED jj\n  opfork-wedge reproduction (or documented non-reproduction + implication).\n\nDEPENDS ON: none (entry point).\nCONTEXT POINTERS: notes/manifold-v2.md section 2.2 (opfork mechanism) ;\nmemory: maw-design-rationale-agent-fluency ; Claude Agent SDK / CLI agents\nas candidate drivers.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","benchmark","spike"],"parent":"bn-2jwi","size":"m","title":"SP3 (spike) Agent-benchmark feasibility + fair-jj reproduction"}	blake3:LHAiTzEyqADi6njIiEjZlAUsZCXV17wCM5BmUn5JzfA
1778965656203007	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyoA8		item.create	bn-4qwp	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nFactor T1.2's generator behind an interface consumed by BOTH the cheap\nmodel/oracle driver (SG1) and the expensive real-agent driver (T2.2):\nbuild the generator once, drive it two ways.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- SG1's DST and the SG2 agent driver both consume the same generator crate\n  with no fork/copy.\n- Same seed yields the same scenario regardless of driver.\n\nDEPENDS ON: T1.2, SP3.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: T1.1 design (generator interface section) ; T1.2.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","benchmark"],"parent":"bn-2jwi","size":"m","title":"T2.1 Factor the shared scenario interface (from T1.2)"}	blake3:C3PsCilWEZcB3o7NbbvYazrpSThkaG8ucSiQSJIEMmc
1778965656443680	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyoQ8		item.create	bn-1sqo	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nSpawn fresh-context agents to complete a fixed multi-agent task battery\nagainst a pluggable substrate; capture full transcript + metrics. Fresh\ncontext is the point: it tests whether self-describing tool output\novercomes an out-of-training-distribution tool.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Reproducible (within the variance SP3 measured) given a seed + fixed\n  battery.\n- Emits per-run: tool-calls, turns, transcript, and the raw events T2.4\n  needs.\n\nDEPENDS ON: SP3, T2.7 (pre-registration must be frozen before any\nmeasured runs).\nCONTEXT POINTERS: SP3 memo ; memory: agent-fluency principle.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","benchmark"],"parent":"bn-2jwi","size":"l","title":"T2.2 Build the real-agent driver harness"}	blake3:iKdnx1iEQSJUuPbxxF9RYn4joc0afvoMgTfi69TadKs
1778965656712042	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyog8		item.create	bn-mit2	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nThree adapters presenting EQUIVALENT task semantics so measured\ndifferences reflect substrate ergonomics, not task wording. The\ngit-worktrees arm gets a thin hand-rolled coordination convention (the\nhonest baseline maw is compared against); jj uses jj-workspaces.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Identical task battery runs on all three adapters.\n- Adapter parity reviewed (no adapter does extra work that biases metrics).\n\nDEPENDS ON: SP3.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: notes/manifold-v2.md section 3 (worktrees baseline) ;\nSP3 jj reproduction.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","benchmark"],"parent":"bn-2jwi","size":"l","title":"T2.3 Substrate adapters: maw / git-worktrees+convention / jj"}	blake3:HCVJfdeDRGCIecYKz9T6k2jx9ZsgM_iTI4uT3AQudj4
1778965656959147	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyow8		item.create	bn-oko4	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nRecord per-run, NEVER averaged into a single score: tool-calls,\nturns-to-done, work-lost events, work-redone / wasted-turns, human-\nintervention events. Reporting shows efficiency vs correctness separately\n(a dominance argument).\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Output is a per-run table; report renders efficiency and correctness as\n  distinct axes (no composite).\n- Definitions of each metric are written down and stable.\n\nDEPENDS ON: T2.2.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","benchmark"],"parent":"bn-2jwi","size":"m","title":"T2.4 Metrics instrumentation (non-composited, dominance)"}	blake3:Fd22a9FvV9ReWrdrHrSyZ-wuH80USw5Mcd-a3aFIwdo
1778965657215606	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEypA8		item.create	bn-1rgk	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nAttribute wasted turns to specific maw verbs/states (structured-conflict\nworkspace, stale-workspace misread, --abort/retry, scarce maw vocabulary).\nFailure asymmetry: worktrees/jj LOSE/WEDGE work; maw PRESERVES it but may\ncost recovery turns — so this, not \"work lost\" (~0 for maw by design), is\nmaw's interesting metric and the instrument for confidence gap #2.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Each wasted-turn cluster is attributed to a named maw verb/state with\n  transcript evidence.\n- Output is the input format T2.8 consumes.\n\nDEPENDS ON: T2.2, T2.4.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: memory: agent-fluency principle (maw's own\nvocabulary scarcity; self-describing output as the mitigation).\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","benchmark"],"parent":"bn-2jwi","size":"m","title":"T2.5 maw-specific diagnostic metric (per-verb/state attribution)"}	blake3:3SJ5F18tVkGXedriykuKIUj1un5Jp7ORlYitS6eSUy0
1778965657470922	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEypQ8		item.create	bn-3l1f	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nRun benign->hostile conditions and compute, per substrate, the CROSSOVER\npoint: below it maw is overkill; above it worktrees lose work and jj\nopfork-wedges. The crossover curve is the publishable headline.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- A curve per substrate over the condition axis with the crossover\n  identified and confidence stated.\n- The regime where maw LOSES (overkill) is included, not hidden.\n\nDEPENDS ON: T2.2, T2.3, T2.4, T2.7 (pre-registration frozen first).\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","benchmark"],"parent":"bn-2jwi","size":"m","title":"T2.6 Condition-spectrum sweep + crossover analysis"}	blake3:t7FghXe2kqrnAUlupmfE9w3N6l2-p3kklThqLQYSMWw
1778965657725428	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEypg8		item.create	bn-2ftq	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nFreeze, before a single measured run: pass/fail thresholds, the dominance\n(non-composite) presentation, the condition spectrum, and an explicit\ncommitment to publish the regime where maw loses/overkills. This is the\ndiscipline against double-investment bias (wanting both the old ws/ layout\nvindicated and the layout changed).\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Doc committed and timestamped strictly before T2.2/T2.6 runs.\n- States numeric pass/fail bars for the SG3 layout gate (T3.5) and SG4\n  targets (T4.3).\n\nDEPENDS ON: SP3 (you can only pre-register what SP3 showed is measurable).\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","benchmark"],"parent":"bn-2jwi","size":"s","title":"T2.7 Pre-registration doc (write + freeze BEFORE any runs)"}	blake3:wPJpTKt444TkEKMvYR-o7F-PZlhNGz7zSrQXS-gEvDk
1778965657988444	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEypw8		item.create	bn-u9iy	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nProduce the ranked list of maw verbs/states costing agents turns, with\ntranscript evidence, ordered by measured cost. This is SG4's input;\nhardening cannot start without it.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Ranked list with per-item measured cost + evidence.\n- Handed to SG4/T4.1. BLOCKS SG4.\n\nDEPENDS ON: T2.5, T2.6.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","benchmark"],"parent":"bn-2jwi","size":"s","title":"T2.8 Diagnostic report -> prioritized maw friction list"}	blake3:dDj5FgTwwej1O5pYF1YlHv1OR5TgM59kdNapRjb4VdU
1778965657988639	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyqA8		item.link	bn-2j45	{"link_type":"blocks","target":"bn-u9iy"}	blake3:7543GkZljPRomCPe04q8RH9jbHaQXh50Uf7qj6ZmrS4
1778965658222442	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyqQ8		item.create	bn-gh1p	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nValidate the load-bearing assumption that moving to \"root = a normal\ncheckout that ALSO is the merge target, agent worktrees under hidden\n.maw/worktrees/\" is RELOCATION, not a rewrite, of the merge engine —\nbefore committing to T3.2 (xl).\n\nWHAT WE DON'T KNOW\nThe \"relocation not rewrite\" claim is an assertion from a code read, not\nvalidated. We must enumerate every place the engine assumes a bare root /\nws/ layout and confirm the privileged-root-checkout update path already\nexists and suffices.\n\nAPPROACH\nOn a throwaway repo, hand-construct the target layout and exercise\ncreate -> commit -> merge -> destroy -> recover. Trace which code paths\nassume bare-root/ws/. Pay specific attention to merge.rs\nsync_target_worktree_to_epoch + handle_post_merge_destroy and\nff_absorb.rs (the existing privileged-target update logic), and\nworkspace_path/discovery.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Prototype runs the full lifecycle on the new layout.\n- Written engine-impact assessment enumerating every layout assumption,\n  each classified trivial-relocation vs real-rewrite, with a go/no-go for\n  T3.1/T3.2.\n\nDEPENDS ON: none (entry point).\nCONTEXT POINTERS: crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/merge.rs\n(sync_target_worktree_to_epoch, handle_post_merge_destroy) ;\ncrates/maw-cli/src/workspace/ff_absorb.rs ;\ncrates/maw-cli/src/workspace/ (workspace_path, discovery) ;\nnotes/bare-repo-architecture-v2.md ; memory: agent-fluency principle\n(layout under reconsideration; Claude Code .claude/ precedent).\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","layout","spike"],"parent":"bn-2yh1","size":"m","title":"SP4 (spike) Layout engine-impact prototype"}	blake3:gH7JlEIMM9AieIdRbd1F3UOeOcpGjuEgnSDXpoU2-_g
1778965658482408	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyqg8		item.create	bn-tmt8	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nFrom SP4's findings, specify the new layout precisely: root = normal\ncheckout doubling as merge target; agent worktrees under .maw/worktrees/;\ndiscovery, workspace_path resolution, .gitignore semantics; how the engine\nupdates the privileged root checkout; and the v2 ws/ -> new-layout\nmigration.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Design reviewed; explicitly grounded in SP4's go/no-go and assumption\n  list.\n- Migration approach for existing v2 repos specified (feeds T3.3).\n\nDEPENDS ON: SP4.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: SP4 assessment ; notes/bare-repo-architecture-v2.md.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","layout"],"parent":"bn-2yh1","size":"m","title":"T3.1 Layout design doc + migration/back-compat plan"}	blake3:1pc-2oSHnGxQyGoKRgk3ojoJLenrN7AZKgdahhzgARU
1778965658736199	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyqw8		item.create	bn-2sw3	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nImplement T3.1: discovery, workspace_path resolution, init, the .maw/\nadmin dir, and target=root wiring. The merge engine's BEHAVIOUR must not\nchange — only path/discovery/target wiring.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Full test suite green on the new layout (the existing DST/chaos\n  scenarios pass unchanged in behaviour).\n- No regression in bn-cm63 / bn-2wyh / bn-3bbc guarantees.\n\nDEPENDS ON: T3.1, SP4.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: T3.1 design ; crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","layout"],"parent":"bn-2yh1","size":"xl","title":"T3.2 Implement the new layout"}	blake3:P4IbmWTskYE4i_2AgzlrVMzRTOkEc_ta6AYAYeAQPEk
1778965658996027	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyrA8		item.create	bn-3kkl	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nExtend `maw upgrade` (or a new path) to convert a populated v2 ws/ repo to\nthe new layout WITHOUT violating the Prime Invariant during migration.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Migrating a populated v2 repo (multiple workspaces, recovery refs) loses\n  nothing; `maw doctor` clean afterward; the DST oracles pass on the\n  migrated repo.\n\nDEPENDS ON: T3.2.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: existing `maw upgrade` (v1 .workspaces/ -> v2) as the\npattern ; refs/manifold/* must survive migration.\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","layout"],"parent":"bn-2yh1","size":"l","title":"T3.3 Migration path for existing v2 ws/ repos"}	blake3:vJxNAFlwlMX3zhZvLs66P8pLw7B7wUIsyF7F_fjcHuc
1778965659248286	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyrQ8		item.create	bn-1jqo	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nThe current ws/ layout exists partly to make it evident agents must not\nedit root files / skip maw. With a normal root, enforce that via the path\nhanded to the agent + AGENTS.md + an optional guard hook — NOT via layout.\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- With the new layout, agents reliably stay in their workspace in the SP3\n  harness (no root-file edits) without the ws/ cue.\n- The guardrail mechanism is documented.\n\nDEPENDS ON: T3.2.\nCONTEXT POINTERS: memory: agent-fluency principle (guardrail is an\nagent-instruction concern, not a layout one).\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","layout"],"parent":"bn-2yh1","size":"m","title":"T3.4 Relocate the anti-skip guardrail off the layout"}	blake3:_suAPp5-mMI0_C4koT_xRdBq8s2X4gC-o6P2xnGmeFM
1778965659513761	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyrg8		item.create	bn-1uzn	{"description":"OBJECTIVE\nRun new-layout vs current through SG2's battery against T2.7's\npre-registered bar and RECORD the decision: merge layout into v1.0 iff no\nagent regression; else defer (it must NOT block the trust artifact).\n\nACCEPTANCE CRITERIA\n- Eval run with the frozen T2.7 criteria; written go/no-go with the data.\n- If no-go: an explicit note that v1.0 ships on SG1 alone and layout is the\n  immediate follow-up. GATES SG5.\n\nDEPENDS ON: T3.4, T2.2 (needs the agent harness), T2.7 (the frozen bar).\n","kind":"task","labels":["v1-0","layout"],"parent":"bn-2yh1","size":"m","title":"T3.5 Pre-registered layout ergonomics eval + go/no-go gate"}	blake3:0HJ3QLgNtqPdyNxVI_NOEuX3FvL1tYNf-AHmUSChkJY
