1779908240362687	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy0hE		item.create	bn-3hzt	{"description":"2026-05-27 lead observation: SG2's work_lost metric is consistently 0\nacross all arms because Oracle B's truth (\"any committed blob is\nreachable\") is hard to violate — that's the Prime Invariant working.\nBUT the agent's BELIEF that work was lost (ws_recover_invoked cluster\nfired 11/60 runs in SG2 N=10) is the actual ergonomic signal, and\nwe're not pushing hard enough to make it surface differentially\nacross substrates.\n\nCurrent state:\n- SG1 in-proc driver supports FaultSpec injection via FP_* failpoints\n  (T1.5 bn-263u shipped; bn-2017 isolated REGISTRY for parallel tests).\n- SG2 ConditionProfile knobs (mid_op_kill_prob etc.) flow to the SG1\n  in-proc generator but the SG2 agent driver IGNORES them\n  (substrate adapters spawn agents against substrates with no chaos).\n- Pre-reg §1.2 currently states \"fault injection is SG1's domain;\n  SG2 keeps failure modes orthogonal\" — this bone proposes relaxing\n  that constraint as a documented amendment.\n\nMotivation: the credibility move for v1.0 — \"we crashed maw mid-merge\nand the agent recovered with N extra turns; we did the same to jj and\nthe agent wedged; we did the same to worktrees+convention and the\nagent declared the workspace dead.\" This is the failure-asymmetry\nstory SG4 has been chasing without the chaos overlay to actually\nproduce it.\n\nAcceptance:\n1. Pre-reg amendment in notes/sg2-benchmark-preregistration.md §1.2:\n   SG2 may apply FaultSpec injection via MAW_FP env passed to the\n   agent's spawned tool subprocess. Documented amendment with\n   rationale + the publication framing.\n2. MawAdapter (crates/maw-bench-adapters/src/maw_adapter.rs) accepts\n   an optional FaultSpec stream (likely via SubstrateHandle extension\n   or per-call env override) and sets MAW_FP=... in the env the\n   spawned agent inherits. Per scenario step the agent's NEXT maw\n   invocation triggers the configured failpoint.\n3. The faithful maw binary (--features failpoints) becomes a\n   prerequisite for chaos-enabled SG2 runs. Eval bin preflight (from\n   bn-f5zu) extends to detect \"installed maw doesn't have failpoints\n   enabled\" and warn that chaos-mode is no-op.\n4. WorktreesConventionAdapter + JjAdapter get analogous chaos seams\n   where applicable (git/jj don't have the same failpoint hooks; for\n   parity, the chaos is at the substrate-process-kill layer:\n   SIGKILL the agent's currently-running git/jj subprocess at a\n   random point during merge). Documented in adapter parity table\n   (notes/sg2-adapter-parity.md update).\n5. New `--chaos=on|off` flag on sg2-sweep-pilot + sg3-layout-eval\n   bins. Default off (back-compat). Wire ConditionProfile.mid_op_kill_prob\n   into chaos enforcement when --chaos=on.\n6. Smoke test: one chaos-enabled cell run (mock seed planted to\n   trigger FP_COMMIT failpoint mid-merge). Asserts:\n   - the agent observes a partial-merge state\n   - either recovers (maw) or wedges (jj/worktrees) per substrate\n   - oracle_b stays Green for maw (Prime Invariant); may go Red for\n     worktrees/jj depending on what they actually do\n7. cargo check + cargo test --workspace + cargo clippy --workspace\n   --all-targets -- -D warnings — all green.\n\nNon-goals:\n- Running the chaos-enabled campaign (separate calendar bone after\n  this wires in).\n- Implementing new failpoints in maw itself (use existing FP_*\n  set; if a needed one is missing, NOTE it and defer).\n- Fault injection on the substrate filesystem layer (out of scope:\n  we drive chaos at the verb-subprocess level, not the FS).\n\nCalendar / cost note:\n- Implementation: bone-sized; ~half-day agent work.\n- First chaos-enabled SG2 mini run (1 chaos cell, N=3 per arm =\n  9 runs): ~$1.50 quota burn.\n- First chaos-enabled SG3 layout-eval (same shape as SG3 today, but\n  with chaos at SUB-B): ~$10-12 quota burn.\n\nPredecessors: bn-263u (T1.5 fault layer), bn-mit2 (adapters),\nbn-1h4b (eval-bin wire-up), bn-f5zu (version-skew preflight).\nDoes NOT block: bn-3uj4 (v1.0-pre.1 cut) — chaos wire-up is a\nv1.0 final / dogfood-window deliverable, not pre.1-gating.\nBlocks: bn-3ctu (v1.0 final / SG5 publication) — the\nfailure-asymmetry story we publish needs this evidence.\n","kind":"task","labels":["benchmark","v1-0"],"parent":"bn-142y","size":"m","title":"Wire SG1 fault-injection into SG2 agent driver — crash-recovery as agent-ergonomics signal"}	blake3:2RivHgZ67LVWnBDzxbOOalkBM0Iwq-kksotczTOejTs
